<div id="review_3155588423" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3155588423" />
    <a title="Julie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1224976-julie"><img alt="Julie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560774654p2/1224976.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3155588423?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julie" href="/user/show/1224976-julie">Julie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/20034254-consider-the-fork">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1224976-julie?shelf=health">health</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1224976-julie?shelf=finished-2020">finished-2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3155588423" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12531997122081851518">Well, that was a fun read! Perfect for my subway commuting book - nothing too deep or taxing to cause me to miss my train stop. I also learned lots of random fun facts, perfect for boring those around me! It&apos;s a win-win haha.<br/><br/>Some facts to ponder:<br/><br/>Rice cookers aren&apos;t good for long grain rices, only short grain. - I had no idea. Whoops.<br/><br/>The overbite is a recent aspect of human anatomy and probably results from the way we use our table knives. This has only been the normal alignment of the human jaw </span>
  <span id="freeText12531997122081851518" style="display:none">Well, that was a fun read! Perfect for my subway commuting book - nothing too deep or taxing to cause me to miss my train stop. I also learned lots of random fun facts, perfect for boring those around me! It's a win-win haha.<br /><br />Some facts to ponder:<br /><br />Rice cookers aren't good for long grain rices, only short grain. - I had no idea. Whoops.<br /><br />The overbite is a recent aspect of human anatomy and probably results from the way we use our table knives. This has only been the normal alignment of the human jaw for 200 to 250 years in the Western world. Before that, most human beings had an edge-to-edge bite, comparable to apes. - I'm having a hard time picturing Henry VIII with a toothy grin like a chimpanzee.<br /><br />The roast beef of England reflected a densely wooded landscape, and the fact that there was plenty of grass for grazing animals. The English could afford to cook entire beasts beside the heat of a fierce fire, throwing on as many logs as it took. - I never considered how the amount of firewood available affected a country's cuisine!<br /><br />Gas powered heat was the single greatest improvement ever (EVER) to occur in kitchen technology. It liberated millions from the pollution, discomfort &amp; sheer time wasting of looking after a fire. - Go kiss your gas powered stove right now!<br /><br />Only the United States uses the weirdness of measuring food in cups instead of by weight or volume. - Again, I had no idea how weird we were for doing this!<br /><br />In 1959, 96% of American households had a refrigerator. In Britain only 13% did. - , 13%. That is so incredible.<br /><br />in 1917, 25% of American homes were on the electric grid. By 1930, 80% were. - We were busy in the 1920s!<br /><br />In 1970, only 3.5% of British people had a freezer. - Where did they store their pints of ice cream? I'm so confused.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12531997122081851518" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


