<div id="review_2652002639" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2652002639" />
    <a title="Gillyz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/71260076-gillyz"><img alt="Gillyz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560415708p2/71260076.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2652002639?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gillyz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gillyz" href="/user/show/71260076-gillyz">Gillyz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/71260076-gillyz?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/71260076-gillyz?shelf=curiosity">curiosity</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2652002639" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4690253154704627993">First of all, I am no expert at all, I just love reading and sometimes I pick random books to enrich my knowledge, which was the case for &apos;Consider the Fork&apos;.<br/><br/>The book provided me with lots of interesting information that I will love to share in casual conversations.<br/>However, I am compelled to dispute some of the information provided / omitted:<br/> <br/>1- Are French and Chinese cuisines widely considered to be the two greatest in the world? As far as I know, Italy&apos;s cuisine is widely considered to be the </span>
  <span id="freeText4690253154704627993" style="display:none">First of all, I am no expert at all, I just love reading and sometimes I pick random books to enrich my knowledge, which was the case for 'Consider the Fork'.<br /><br />The book provided me with lots of interesting information that I will love to share in casual conversations.<br />However, I am compelled to dispute some of the information provided / omitted:<br /> <br />1- Are French and Chinese cuisines widely considered to be the two greatest in the world? As far as I know, Italy's cuisine is widely considered to be the greatest in the world. As a matter of fact, I believe the Italian cuisine is highly neglected in the book as it focus on the French cuisine, when many of the subjects in discussion actually had their origin in Italian territory.  <br /><br />2. The chapter about coffee is so short and poor that it would have been better not to include it. The very famous and traditional italian Moka pot or the Neapolitan flip coffee pot were completely ignored. No mention on Brazilian, Colombian or Vietnamese coffee either. <br /><br />3- The author writes like as if it's common to find in South America people who still use primitives "smoky fires" to cook and affirms South Americans refuse any modernity offered by aid workers. Well, I have been many times in South America and I have never seen such a thing in Argentina, Brazil, Ecuador, Paraguay, Colombia, Peru (my knowledge of this particular country is limited to the capital), or Uruguay. Even in slums they use modern stoves. <br />Could it be possible she meant the native indigenous people who live within the Amazon forests? it would be better if she could specify where these people are located instead of putting a huge contient within a tiny basket.<br />Note: I often travel to 4 Maghreb Countries and never have I seen any smoky fire there either. <br /><br />4- There are other countries that use Cup Measures, it isn't only the USA as stated in the book. For instance, Brazil is one of them, and they have several different kinds of spoons, cups and so forth. The most used cup measure in Brazil is the unique "Copo de requeijao" (Cup of Requeijao) - requeijao is a Brazilan cream cheese, which is almost always sold within a cup.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4690253154704627993" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


